SIMPLE: people
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: People
<hw>Peo"ple</hw> <pr>(p⟦emac⟧"p'l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>peple</ets>, <ets>people</ets>, OF. <ets>pueple</ets>, F.
<ets>peuple</ets>, fr. L. <ets>populus</ets>. Cf. <er>Populage</er>,
<er>Public</er>, <er>Pueblo</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The body of
persons who compose a community, tribe, nation, or race; an aggregate of
individuals forming a whole; a community; a nation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unto him shall the gathering of the <qex>people</qex> be.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. xlix. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ants are a <qex>people</qex> not strong.</q> <rj><qau>Prov.
xxx. 25.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Before many <qex>peoples</qex>, and nations, and tongues.</q>
<rj><qau>Rev. x. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Earth's monarchs are her <qex>peoples</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Whitter.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A government of all the <qex>people</qex>, by all the
<qex>people</qex>, for all the <qex>people</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>T.
Parker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>People</xex>is a collective noun, generally
construed with a plural verb, and only occasionally used in the plural
form (<xex>peoples</xex>), in the sense of nations or races.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Persons, generally; an indefinite number of men and
women; folks; population, or part of population; <as>as, country
<ex>people</ex></as>; -- sometimes used as an indefinite subject or
verb, like <xex>on</xex> in French, and <xex>man</xex> in German;
<as>as, <ex>people</ex> in adversity</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>People</qex> were tempted to lend by great premiums.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>People</qex> have lived twenty-four days upon nothing but
water.</q> <rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The mass of community as distinguished from a
special class; the commonalty; the populace; the vulgar; the common
crowd; <as>as, nobles and <ex>people</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And strive to gain his pardon from the <qex>people</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> With a possessive pronoun: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>One's
ancestors or family; kindred; relations; <as>as, my <ex>people</ex> were
English</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>One's subjects; fellow citizens;
companions; followers.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧You slew great number of his
<xex>people</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>People</er>, <er>Nation</er>.</syn> <usage>
When speaking of a state, we use <xex>people</xex> for the mass of the
community, as distinguished from their rulers, and <xex>nation</xex> for
the entire political body, including the rulers. In another sense of the
term, <xex>nation</xex> describes those who are descended from the same
stock; and in this sense the Germans regard themselves as one
<xex>nation</xex>, though politically subject to different forms of
government.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>People</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: People
<hw>Peo"ple</hw> <pr>(p⟦emac⟧"p'l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Peopled</conjf>
<pr>(p⟦emac⟧"p'ld)</pr> <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>;
<conjf>Peopling</conjf> <pr>(p⟦emac⟧"p'l⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[Cf. OF. <ets>popler</ets>, <ets>puepler</ets>, F.
<ets>puepler</ets>. Cf. <er>Populate</er>.]</ety> <def>To stock with
people or inhabitants; to fill as with people; to populate.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Peopled</xex> heaven with angels.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As the gay motes that <qex>people</qex> the sunbeams.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peopled</ent>⟦br⟧
